n and George Campbell Hay -- t17 Living with the Double Tongue: Modern Poetry in Scots -- t18 Monsters and Goddesses: Culture Re-energised in the Poetry of Ruaraidh MacThòmais and Aonghas MacNeacail -- t19 Old Country, New Dreams: Scottish Poetry since the 1970s -- t20 The Lost Boys and Girls of Scottish Children’s Fiction -- t21 The Human and Textual Condition: Muriel Spark’s Narratives -- t22 From Carswell to Kay: Aspects of Gender, the Novel and the Drama -- t23 The Autobiography in Scottish Gaelic -- t24 Varieties of Voice and Changing Contexts: Robin Jenkins and Janice Galloway -- t25 Breaking Boundaries: From Modern to Contemporary in Scottish Fiction -- t26 Re-imagining the City: End of the Century Cultural Signs in the Novels of McIlvanney, Banks, Gray, Welsh, Kelman, Owens and Rankin -- t27 The Border Crossers and Reconfiguration of the Possible: Poet-Playwright-Novelists from the Mid-Twentieth Century on -- t28 In the Shadow of the Bard: The Gaelic Short Story, Novel and Drama since the early Twentieth Century -- t29 Staging the Nation: Multiplicity and Cultural Diversity in Contemporary Scottish Theatre -- t30 Varieties of Gender Politics, Sexuality and Thematic Innovation in Late Twentieth-Century Drama -- t31 The Diaspora and its Writers -- t32 New Diversity, Hybridity and Scottishness -- tNotes on Contributors – Volume Three -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn almost a century since the First World War ended, Scotland has been transformed in many rich ways. Its literature has been an essential part of that transformation. The third volume of the History explores the vibrancy of modern Scottish literature in all its forms and languages. Giving full credit to writing in Gaelic and by the Scottish diaspora, it brings together the best contemporary critical insights from three continents. It provides an accessible and refreshing picture of both the varieties of Scottish literatures and the kaleidoscopic versions of Scotland that mark literary developments since 1918.Other volumes in the HistoryThe Edinburgh History of Scottish Literature, Volume 1: From Columba to the Union (until 1707)The Edinburgh History of Scottish Literature, Volume 2: Enlightenment, Britain and Empire (1707-1918)Key FeaturesOriginal - presents new approaches to what is literature and what is ScottishnessInclusive - Gaelic and diasporic writing, Latin writing, theological writing, legal writing, and context chaptersComprehensive - provides the fullest coverage of Scottish literature ever and the first survey for almost 20 yearsDistinguished contributors from many countriesInfluences the agenda for critical debate on Scottish writing in the twenty-first century"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aEnglish literaturexScottish authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aLittérature écossaise (anglaise)xHistoire et critique. 0aLittérature écossaisexHistoire et critiquexSchotland. 0aScottish literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aScottish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Reference.2bisacsh1 aBarnaby, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBateman, Meg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButt, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByrne, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClancy, Thomas Owen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1